A folder full of notes is useful right up until it stops being searchable in any meaningful way.

File names help a little. Full-text search helps a little more. But neither can answer a question like:

• Which notes mention evaluation methods for retrieval systems?
• What did I write about OCR pipelines that also touched document structure?
• Which project ideas are similar to this draft I started last week?

A practical fix is to build semantic search over your own files.

This article shows how to create a small local search tool in Python that turns a folder of text documents into a searchable vector index. You will be able to ask for the most relevant notes by meaning, not just by exact keyword match.

The approach is simple:

• read files from a folder
• split them into chunks
• convert chunks into embeddings
• store them in a local index
• run similarity search for any query

It is fast to build, cheap to run, and useful for research notes, project docs, article drafts, meeting summaries, and internal knowledge bases.

⸻

Why semantic search is worth building

Traditional search matches words.

Semantic search matches intent and meaning.

That difference matters when your notes use different wording for the same idea. A note about “document parsing” should still be found when you search for “extract structured data from PDFs.” A draft about “model confidence” should still appear when you ask for “uncertainty estimation.”

This is one of the most useful small AI systems you can build because it solves a real workflow problem without requiring a giant application.

You also keep control of your data if everything runs locally.

⸻

What we are building

The tool will:

• scan a folder for .txt and .md files
• split each file into overlapping chunks
• create embeddings with a sentence-transformers model
• store vectors in a FAISS index
• return the top matching chunks for a query

This is enough to create a working local knowledge search system.

Later, you can extend it with:

• PDF support
• metadata filters
• a desktop UI
• re-ranking
• question answering on top of retrieved chunks

⸻

Project structure

A minimal project can look like this:

semantic_notes/
search_notes.py
notes/
idea_1.md
meeting_notes.txt
draft_article.md

Install the dependencies:

pip install sentence-transformers faiss-cpu numpy

If you want to keep things lightweight, this setup is a good balance between simplicity and quality.

⸻

Step 1 → Load files from a folder

Start by collecting note files.

import os

def load_documents(folder_path):
    documents = []
    for root, _, files in os.walk(folder_path):
        for file in files:
            if file.endswith(".txt") or file.endswith(".md"):
                path = os.path.join(root, file)
                with open(path, "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
                    text = f.read().strip()
                    if text:
                        documents.append({
                            "path": path,
                            "text": text
                        })
    return documents

This function walks through the folder and loads plain text and Markdown files into memory.

⸻

Step 2 → Split documents into chunks

Embedding entire documents can work for short notes, but chunking usually gives better retrieval. It helps the system return the exact section that matches the query.

def chunk_text(text, chunk_size=500, overlap=100):
    chunks = []
    start = 0
    while start < len(text):
        end = start + chunk_size
        chunk = text[start:end]
        chunks.append(chunk)
        start += chunk_size - overlap
    return chunks

def create_chunks(documents, chunk_size=500, overlap=100):
    all_chunks = []
    for doc in documents:
        chunks = chunk_text(doc["text"], chunk_size, overlap)
        for i, chunk in enumerate(chunks):
            all_chunks.append({
                "path": doc["path"],
                "chunk_id": i,
                "text": chunk
            })
    return all_chunks

This version uses character-based chunking because it is easy to understand and works well enough for many note collections.

For production use, sentence-aware chunking is often better, but this is a strong starting point.

⸻

Step 3 → Create embeddings

Now convert each chunk into a vector representation.

from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer
import numpy as np

model = SentenceTransformer("all-MiniLM-L6-v2")

def embed_chunks(chunks):
    texts = [chunk["text"] for chunk in chunks]
    embeddings = model.encode(texts, convert_to_numpy=True, show_progress_bar=True)
    return embeddings

The model all-MiniLM-L6-v2 is a popular default:

• small
• fast
• good enough for many semantic search tasks

If your note collection is specialized, you can later test stronger embedding models.

⸻

Step 4 → Build a FAISS index

FAISS is a fast similarity search library that works well for local vector search.

import faiss

def build_faiss_index(embeddings):
    dimension = embeddings.shape[1]
    index = faiss.IndexFlatL2(dimension)
    index.add(embeddings.astype(np.float32))
    return index

This uses L2 distance. For many embedding models, cosine similarity is also common. A simple way to approximate cosine similarity in FAISS is to normalize vectors before indexing.

Here is the improved version:

def normalize_embeddings(embeddings):
    norms = np.linalg.norm(embeddings, axis=1, keepdims=True)
    return embeddings / norms

def build_faiss_index_cosine(embeddings):
    normalized = normalize_embeddings(embeddings).astype(np.float32)
    dimension = normalized.shape[1]
    index = faiss.IndexFlatIP(dimension)
    index.add(normalized)
    return index, normalized

Inner product on normalized vectors gives cosine-style similarity.

⸻

Step 5 → Search the notes

Now create a function that embeds a query and retrieves the closest chunks.

def search(query, model, index, chunks, top_k=5):
    query_embedding = model.encode([query], convert_to_numpy=True)
    query_embedding = normalize_embeddings(query_embedding).astype(np.float32)

    scores, indices = index.search(query_embedding, top_k)

    results = []
    for score, idx in zip(scores[0], indices[0]):
        results.append({
            "score": float(score),
            "path": chunks[idx]["path"],
            "chunk_id": chunks[idx]["chunk_id"],
            "text": chunks[idx]["text"]
        })
    return results

This returns the top matching chunks along with their source file paths.

⸻

Step 6 → Put everything together

Here is a complete script you can run.

import os
import numpy as np
import faiss
from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer

def load_documents(folder_path):
    documents = []
    for root, _, files in os.walk(folder_path):
        for file in files:
            if file.endswith(".txt") or file.endswith(".md"):
                path = os.path.join(root, file)
                with open(path, "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
                    text = f.read().strip()
                    if text:
                        documents.append({
                            "path": path,
                            "text": text
                        })
    return documents

def chunk_text(text, chunk_size=500, overlap=100):
    chunks = []
    start = 0
    while start < len(text):
        end = start + chunk_size
        chunks.append(text[start:end])
        start += chunk_size - overlap
    return chunks

def create_chunks(documents, chunk_size=500, overlap=100):
    all_chunks = []
    for doc in documents:
        chunks = chunk_text(doc["text"], chunk_size, overlap)
        for i, chunk in enumerate(chunks):
            all_chunks.append({
                "path": doc["path"],
                "chunk_id": i,
                "text": chunk
            })
    return all_chunks

def normalize_embeddings(embeddings):
    norms = np.linalg.norm(embeddings, axis=1, keepdims=True)
    return embeddings / norms

def build_index(chunks, model):
    texts = [chunk["text"] for chunk in chunks]
    embeddings = model.encode(texts, convert_to_numpy=True, show_progress_bar=True)
    embeddings = normalize_embeddings(embeddings).astype(np.float32)

    dimension = embeddings.shape[1]
    index = faiss.IndexFlatIP(dimension)
    index.add(embeddings)
    return index

def search(query, model, index, chunks, top_k=5):
    query_embedding = model.encode([query], convert_to_numpy=True)
    query_embedding = normalize_embeddings(query_embedding).astype(np.float32)

    scores, indices = index.search(query_embedding, top_k)

    results = []
    for score, idx in zip(scores[0], indices[0]):
        results.append({
            "score": float(score),
            "path": chunks[idx]["path"],
            "chunk_id": chunks[idx]["chunk_id"],
            "text": chunks[idx]["text"]
        })
    return results

if __name__ == "__main__":
    folder = "notes"
    model = SentenceTransformer("all-MiniLM-L6-v2")

    documents = load_documents(folder)
    chunks = create_chunks(documents, chunk_size=500, overlap=100)
    index = build_index(chunks, model)

    query = input("Enter your search query: ")
    results = search(query
